input: How can I simulate on the platform ?
actual_output:
To simulate on the Open Brain Platform, you typically follow these general steps:

1. **Select or Create a Model**: Choose an existing model (e.g., single neuron, synaptome, metabolism, NGV unit) or create/customize your own model by changing cellular composition or parameters.

2. **Configure Simulation Parameters**: Set up the simulation conditions such as input stimuli, duration, and recording variables.

3. **Run the Simulation**: Execute the simulation either locally by downloading notebooks or, when available, directly on the platform.

4. **Analyze Results**: Use the platform's tools to visualize and analyze the simulation output.

Currently, the platform supports running notebooks remotely for models like metabolism and NGV unit, and single neuron or synaptome simulations. The feature to run simulations directly on the platform will be available soon.

If you want, I can guide you through specific simulation types or help you find models to simulate. Would you like to start with a particular model or brain region?

input: What are some recent studies on neuron morphology in the cerebrum?
actual_output:
Here are some recent studies on neuron morphology in the cerebrum:

1. **Whole human-brain mapping of single cortical neurons for profiling ...**  
   - Author: Hanchuan Peng  
   - Published: 2023-10-13  
   - Summary: This study proposes adaptive cell tomography (ACTomography), a low-cost, high-throughput approach for imaging and quantifying neuron morphology and distribution at the whole-brain scale in human cortical neurons. It involved imaging 1746 cortical neurons from surgical tissues and postmortem brain.  
   - [Read more](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3771)  
   ![Image](https://www.science.org/cms/asset/c520cdcb-6be6-43a0-8799-b07699533989/keyimage.gif)

2. **A novel approach to cytoarchitectonics: developing an objective framework for the morphological analysis of the cerebral cortex**  
   - Authors: Matija Vid Prkačin, Zdravko Petanjek, Ivan Banovac  
   - Published: 2024-08-12  
   - Summary: This research develops an objective framework for analyzing the morphology of the cerebral cortex, focusing on cytoarchitectonic boundaries defined by cell types.  
   - [Read more](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/neuroanatomy/articles/10.3389/fnana.2024.1441645/full)  
   ![Image](https://images-provider.frontiersin.org/api/ipx/w=1200&f=png/https://www.frontiersin.org/files/Articles/1441645/fnana-18-1441645-HTML/image_m/fnana-18-1441645-g001.jpg)

3. **The impact of neuron morphology on cortical network architecture**  
   - Published: 2022-04-13  
   - Summary: This study explores how neuron morphology influences the architecture of cortical networks, providing insights into the structural-functional relationships in the brain.  
   - [Read more](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9035680/)  
   ![Image](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/static/img/favicons/favicon-32x32.png)

4. **Morphological diversity of single neurons in molecularly defined cell ...**  
   - Author: Zeng, Hongkui  
   - Published: 2021-10-06  
   - Summary: This paper discusses the diversity of neuron morphology in relation to molecularly defined cell types, integrating transcriptomic, electrophysiological, and morphological data for classification.  
   - [Read more](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-021-03941-1)  
   ![Image](https://media.springernature.com/m685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-021-03941-1/MediaObjects/41586_2021_3941_Fig1_HTML.png)

5. **Measurements of neuronal morphological variation across the rat ...**  
   - Author: G.N. Elston  
   - Published: 2020-08-24  
   - Summary: This article measures neuronal morphological variation across different regions in the rat brain, providing comparative data relevant to understanding cerebral neuron morphology.  
   - [Read more](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0304394020303475)  
   ![Image](https://sdfestaticassets-us-east-1.sciencedirectassets.com/shared-assets/103/images/favSD.ico)

If you want more details or papers on a specific aspect of neuron morphology in the cerebrum, please let me know!

actual_output:
Here are some morphologies from the Cerebellum:

1. **Name:** [soma_10c](https://openbraininstitute.org/app/virtual-lab/explore/interactive/experimental/morphology/e892fa95-c724-457a-8dc6-176f5d6cc5d9)  
   - **Description:** Soma as a flask-like shape with a radius around 7.5 µm and close to the sagittal plane. Located in the Purkinje cell layer. Dendrites are flat, large and highly branched named dendritic tree. Located in the molecular layer. There is a single long axon, downward to the white matter. It’s the sole output of the cerebellum.  
   - **Species:** Mus musculus  
   - **Mtype:** Cerebellum Purkinje Cell (CBXpu_PuC)

2. **Name:** [01bc](https://openbraininstitute.org/app/virtual-lab/explore/interactive/experimental/morphology/d083a0bd-00a4-4594-b52f-950a5dd3ec70)  
   - **Description:** The soma is pyramidal or oval with a radius of 6 µm. Located in the 1/3 inner of the molecular layer. The dendrites are long, straight and extend upward to the Pia surface with few branches. The axon measures several hundred of µm and runs parallel to the Purkinje cell layer. There are descending collaterals (thick and run in the sagittal plane) and ascending collaterals (several, thin, short and present in the 2/3 inner of the molecular layer).  
   - **Species:** Mus musculus  
   - **Mtype:** Cerebellum Basket Cell (CBXmo_BC)

3. **Name:** [stellate](https://openbraininstitute.org/app/virtual-lab/explore/interactive/experimental/morphology/00ba95d3-13e4-4703-ad85-3df816febf53)  
   - **Description:** The soma is small and fusiform with a radius around 4 µm. Located in the 2/3 outer of the molecular layer. The dendrites are long, thin, contorted, aspinous and branching in all directions. The axon branches immediately in short and circumscribed collaterals.  
   - **Species:** Mus musculus  
   - **Mtype:** Cerebellum Stellate Cell (CBXmo_StC)

4. **Name:** [pair-140514-C2-1_split_1](https://openbraininstitute.org/app/virtual-lab/explore/interactive/experimental/morphology/cb635d11-f5f4-4ec5-8c6e-3e5af6d4eb6c)  
   - **Description:** The soma is round or polygonal with a radius of 8 µm. Located in the granular layer. Four-ten dendrites emitting from the soma and are divided in two groups. The basal dendrites (thick and contorted) remain in the granular layer and the apical dendrites (stout and straight) ascend toward the molecular layer forming a fan-shaped dendritic tree. The axons are composed by very thin beaded fibers and extend profusely into the granular layer (forming a large axon plexus).  
   - **Species:** Mus musculus  
   - **Mtype:** Cerebellum Golgi Cell (CBXgr_GoC)

5. **Name:** [GrC2018](https://openbraininstitute.org/app/virtual-lab/explore/interactive/experimental/morphology/b03ceac9-d657-488c-a43c-01be275d0861)  
   - **Description:** The soma is very small (radius = 2.5 µm) and round. Located in the granular layer they are the smallest, most densely packed and the most numerous neurons types in the entire brain. There are 4-5 dendrites, end in claw-like appendage. For the axon, the ascending axon segment goes up to the molecular layer and bifurcates within this layer into parallel fiber like a “T”. The parallel fiber runs along the long axis of the folia.  
   - **Species:** Mus musculus  
   - **Mtype:** Cerebellum Granule Cell (CBXgr_GrC)

Would you like to see more morphologies from the Cerebellum?
